I would like to add that extended properties can be used for more than database object descriptions. Extended properties can be used to store label text for forms.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Each database column can have an extended property named &quot;Label&quot; to be used on forms. You fill your form labels with text from the sys tables. Then you only need to change the label text in one place to change it on every form.

I have written a bunch of scripts to help me maintain extended properties in SQL Server.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
http://www.databasezone.com/techdocs/dbscripts.html&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Many of the scripts read the sys tables and write out all of the boilerplate extended property code ready for customization.

On a related note, if you use SSDT to manage your schema, you can also add the definitions to the objects in your database in the &quot;properties&quot; panel which will be propagated into your DB.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Admittedly, that&#039;s not nearly as detailed as what you can do using the techniques in this article, but it can be a good start for people without too much extra work.
